## 🚫 BLOCKER #2: Missing default values for all optional fields

**Same root cause** as BLOCKER #1 — without `parseManifest`, **no defaults are applied**.

### Reference defaults (`.source/soul.ts:457-473`)

| TS field       | Reference default | Current if missing | Impact                                                  |
| -------------- | ----------------- | ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| `spec_version` | `"0.5"`           | `undefined`        | Version check fails                                     |
| `name`         | `"unknown"`       | `undefined`        | Soul name missing                                       |
| `display_name` | `"Unknown"`       | `undefined`        | Empty header in output                                  |
| `version`      | `"1.0.0"`         | `undefined`        | Version display broken                                  |
| `description`  | `""`              | `undefined`        | Renders "undefined" in prompt                           |
| `author.name`  | `"Unknown"`       | `undefined`        | Author display broken                                   |
| `license`      | `"MIT"`           | `undefined`        | License display broken                                  |
| `category`     | `"general"`       | `undefined`        | Category display broken                                 |
| `files.soul`   | `"SOUL.md"`       | `undefined`        | SOUL.md path is empty string → loader skips read        |
| `deprecated`   | `false`           | `undefined`        | Boolean check on undefined is truthy-falsey but fragile |

**Evidence**: `loader.ts:84` casts directly; no defaults are applied before or after.

### Impact

Every field listed above will be `undefined` if absent from `soul.json`, causing runtime display issues in the `system-prompt.ts` builder, `tools.ts` info formatter, and `commands.ts` soul listing.

### Fix

These defaults must be part of the `parseManifest` implementation.

