## 🚫 BLOCKER #3: Legacy `skills: string[]` format not accepted

**Reference** (`.source/soul.ts:361-373`):

```ts
const skillsData = data.recommendedSkills || data.skills || [];
for (const skill of skillsData) {
  if (typeof skill === "string") {
    recommendedSkills.push({ name: skill, required: false });
  } else {
    recommendedSkills.push({
      name: skill.name,
      version: skill.version,
      required: skill.required || false,
    });
  }
}
```

**Current**: `loader.ts:84` — direct cast, no legacy handling.

The spec says tools **MUST** accept the legacy `skills: string[]` format. Without conversion code, a `soul.json` with `"skills": ["skill1", "skill2"]` will result in `recommended_skills` being `undefined` or type-mismatched.

### Impact

Any soul.json using the legacy `skills` format (instead of `recommendedSkills`) will have empty recommended skills. This affects backward compatibility with older soul packages.

### Fix

Include the legacy format handling in the `parseManifest` implementation.

